The Parallel ATA (PATA) interface, also referred to as EIDE, is an older standard used to connect storage devices like hard drives, CD-ROMs, and DVD-ROMs to a computer.

Key features and limitations include:

Cabling: It utilizes a 40-pin ribbon cable that can support two devices per cable.

Configuration: Drives are identified by their position on the cable using jumper settings on the back of the device:
 
Master: The drive connected to the end of the cable 

Slave: The drive connected to the middle connector.

Cable Select: Automatically configures the drive based on its position on the ribbon cable.

Capacity: Older motherboards typically featured two PATA interfaces, allowing for a total of four connected drives.

Performance: The final standard, ATA-133, provided data transfer speeds up to 133 MB/s.

Note: PATA is considered a legacy technology and has been largely replaced by the faster SATA interface, with many modern motherboards offering little to no PATA support
